data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc` with `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both native-sized integer types work as expected:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[5];
```

On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes. The elements are stack-allocated and accessible through the span just like any other unmanaged type. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 (when `nint`/`nuint` became first-class types that satisfy the `unmanaged` constraint).
